1.1. Problem Statement¶

In 2-4 sentences, explain the kind of problem you want to look at and the datasets you will be wrangling for this project.

Since 2009 wit the release of first Low Top designed signature shoe of Kobe Bryant, a trend from High Top Basketball shoes to Low Top Basketball shoes has been observed, and medical studies on a small group of subjects have been performed, in line with the respective zeitgeist at in different eras:

Petrov et al.,1988: Footwear and ankle stability in the basketball player

Barret et.al., 1993 High- versus low-top shoes for the prevention of ankle sprains in basketball players. A prospective randomized study

Ottaviani et. al, 1995: Basketball shoe height and the maximal muscular resistance to applied ankle inversion and eversion moments

Curtis et.al., 2008 The role of shoe design in ankle sprain rates among collegiate basketball players

Current zeitgeist suggests there is no significant increased ankle support with High Tops, while amongst basketball professionals, there is a hypothesis of Low Tops potentially having a performance advantage due to increased ankle mobility, ,the ankle joint, the knee joint, and the hip joint joints work together in a coordinated manner to generate the necessary force and range of motion for an effective vertical jump. This increase in mobility can potentially also prevent ankle sprains, if a player can contract the Anterior Tibialis Muscle faster in Low Tops, e.g. when landing after a jump on even or uneven terrain, with the latter primarily refering to a landing on another players foot during a play.

Since I am unaware of a large scale analysis in regards to this, data of over 5000 games over the last 4 years will be scrapped from a webpage that meticulously tracked stats, as well as what shoe most of the players wore at what game. This data will be merged with another Dataset that tracked the NBA Injury reports, and it will be attempted to draw insights from this merge and wrangling event.

kixstats.com is continually updating a database on most NBA and WNBA games, and for each game the database notes the shoes each player wore in addition to all basic stats. These stats could alternativly be downloaded at an official source, but the uniqueness of this source is the diligent tracking of which shoes each player whore, which makes this source of high potential. # Create list of games in the database
base_url = 'https://kixstats.com/games/NBA?p='
num_pages = 57 # Change this to however many pages you want to scrape

game_list_pages = [base_url + str(page_num) for page_num in range(1, num_pages+1)]

game_list = []
    
for i in game_list_pages:
    
    response = requests.get(i)

    # direct exraction of game list with beatiful soup
    soup = BeautifulSoup(response.content, 'lxml')

    # Find all div elements with class="col-6"
    my_divs = soup.find_all('div', class_=['col-6', 'row'])

    # Get url of game
    for div in my_divs:
        onclick = div.get('onclick')
        if onclick:
            url = onclick.split("'")[1]
            game_list.append(url)

# WEBDRIVER NEEDED TO GET ADDITIONAL STATS - Output will be a complete stats of 1 game

def get_game(url):
    
    # Create a Service object with the path to the ChromeDriver
    chrome_service = Service(executable_path='/Applications/chromedriver')

    # Pass the Service object to the webdriver.Chrome() constructor
    driver = webdriver.Chrome(service=chrome_service)

    # Create an empty DataFrame with the desired column names
    game_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=['Date', 'Player', 'Shoe Name', 'Points', 'Rebounds', 'Assists', 'Steals', 'Blocks','Minutes'])

    # navigate to the webpage
    driver.get(url)

    # find the top-down menu and extract the options
    menu = Select(driver.find_element(By.ID, 'playerstats'))
    options = menu.options

    # loop through each option and extract the data
    for index, option in enumerate(options):
        # select the option in the menu
        menu.select_by_index(index)

        # print the extracted data, and save in variable as identifier 
        option_score = option.text.strip()
    
        # additional time needed to let the webdriver load the web-page to be able to extract option-values 
        time.sleep(.3)
    
        # get the page source - page as rendered with selected options
        page_source = driver.page_source

        # create a BeautifulSoup object
        soup = BeautifulSoup(page_source, 'html.parser')
    
        # extract date to use as identifier
        title_text = soup.find('title').text
        date_str = title_text.split('|')[2].strip().split(' ')[0]

        # find all div tags with class 'row text-center mt-10'
        div_tags = soup.find_all('div', class_='row text-center mt-10')

        # loop through each div tag and extract the desired information
        for div in div_tags:

            # extract player name
            player_name = div.find('div', class_='col-6').text.split("#")[0].strip()

            # extract shoe name
            shoe_name = div.find_all('div', class_='col-6')[1].text.strip()
    
            # extract score
            score = div.find('span', class_='letter-icon').text.strip()
    
            # print the extracted information
            #print(f"Date: {date_str}, Player Name: {player_name}, Shoe Name: {shoe_name},Score for {option_score}:{score}")
        
            # Append the data to the DataFrame as a new row
            row_data = {'Date': date_str, 'Player': player_name, 'Shoe Name': shoe_name, option_score: score}
        
            # Create a DataFrame from the row_data dictionary
            new_df = pd.DataFrame([row_data])
        
            # Concatenate the new_df with the master_df
            game_df = pd.concat([game_df, new_df], ignore_index=True)
        
    # Close the WebDriver
    driver.quit()
    
    # Return aggregated dataframe on Date, Player, and Shoe Name
    return game_df.groupby(['Date', 'Player', 'Shoe Name']).first().reset_index()

Scraping Game Stats In Batches¶

To assure completion and ability to continue from possible interruptions, batches are stored as csv-file for checkpointing, as a backstop, while also directly concatenating to a dataframe of complete game stats

In [13]:
# Function to scrape data from a single page
# get_game()

# List of URLs to scrape
# game_list

def scrape_games(game_list, get_game, batch_size=200):
    '''
    Function to scrape data from all available games of the source page,
    when used with created function get_game() which is the 2. argument.
    '''

    # Batch size
    batch_size = 200
    batches = [game_list[i:i + batch_size] for i in range(0, len(game_list), batch_size)]
    total_batches_no = len(batches)
    
    # Initialize an empty DataFrame to store the final data
    final_games_df = pd.DataFrame()
    batch_no = 1
    
    # Iterate through the URLs in batches
    for i in range(0, len(game_list), batch_size):
        # Initialize an empty DataFrame for the current batch
        batch_df = pd.DataFrame()
    
        # Scrape data for the current batch
        for url in game_list[i:i + batch_size]:
            data = get_game(url)
            # Append the data to the batch DataFrame
            batch_df = pd.concat([batch_df, data], ignore_index=True)
            
        # Concatenate the batch DataFrame to the final DataFrame 
        final_games_df = pd.concat([final_games_df, batch_df], ignore_index=True)
        
        # Additionally store to csv as checkpoint
        batch_df.to_csv(f'batches/batch_{batch_no}.csv', index=False)
        
        print(f"Processed batch {batch_no} of {total_batches_no}...saved")
        
        batch_no += 1      
        # Wait for a few minutes before processing the next batch
        time.sleep(10)
    
    return final_games_df

# a game by one of the players in the dataset

def get_top_list(base_url, num_pages, shoe_list):
    tops_url_list = [base_url if i == 1 else f'{base_url}?page={i}' for i in range(1, num_pages + 1)]

    tops = set()

    for url in tops_url_list:
        response = requests.get(url)
        soup = BeautifulSoup(response.content, 'html.parser')
        product_elements = soup.find_all('a', {'data-v-1e9dcd0a': '', })

        for product_element in product_elements:
            product_name = product_element['href'].split('/')[-1]
            product_name = product_name.replace("-", " ").lower()
            if product_name in shoe_list:
                tops.add(product_name)
    ()
    return list(tops)

Procedure: Classifying players shows according to shoe type proofed to be a somewhat tedious task as there are only limited central classifications available, and the shoe names and signature lines mostly did not specify or adhere to a specific shoe-height but where generally mixed. After attempt to programmatically classify shoe type with an additional web srape, effectively all 600 different shoes have been visually inspected to consider the heigt-cut in regards to ankle support, as this is the main investigative purpose of the project, the general procedural framework was:

  1. If the manufacturer classified a show a certain cut, or added the cut height as part of the shoe-name, if visualy inspection did not contradict the name, the shoe was considered this type, e.g.: 'nike kobe xi low' == low-cut
  2. Retailer classification was considered, e.g. if different retailer or collector classified the shoe a certain cut, for the shoes which are unclear in regards to being between 2 cuts, e.g. low/mid cut, the retailer classification was adhered to.
  3. If no information was available the shoe was inspected and remaining shoes which are unclear and between low/mid cut, where generally considered low-cut, while mid/high cut, where generally considered high cut, and visually clear cuts simply classified according to their cuts.

In a small number of cases, visual inspections contradicted retail classification and it was opted for viscually classification.

Answer 2 to research question: Given plots above, there are first indications that there may be a lesser risk of wearing low tops, it must however be noted that interpretations must be made with caution for the limited data at this point in time (due to reasons mentioned below). In line with professional though there appear to be proportionally less sprained ankles with low tops although low tops account for a larger part of the categorised observations of shoe used overall, whereas mid tops appear to have the proportionaly highest risk of sprained ankles. The underlying logic would be, if findings where confirmed with optimisation of injury data, that mid tops do not let the player dorsi-flex their feet as fast as low tops (dorsi-flexion pulls up the foot/toes towards the shin, which results in a save landing position), while literature suggested there is a minor protection at the actual event-moment of an ankle sprains by high tops.

Please regard the submission at this point as proof of concept, and see below for next needed steps on improvement and consolidation of insights.

5.2: Reflection¶

Answer: Now given the time limit for submission the remaining dataframe is short, the webscraping has high volume data of high quality, however the first dataset, the injury list, is not as complete and comprehensive as would be beneficial, a better solution was for example to scrape the injury report from the source that was used to manually complete the injury information for individual rows, now given the project guidelines it was asked to use at least 2 different methods of data-gathering, hence for the first dataset a direct download was chosen.

Now when having manually completed the intermediate steps before, like manually adding reasons for placement on injury list, like was done in quality issue 1, doing this for all players will again result in an increase in the masked remaining dataset, which should be done before showcasing the project.

Further the project can be expanded to equally investigate achilles tendon injuries, and in regards to performance, the shoe brand and type could both be considered for performance comparisons of athletes.

Limitations: It is not entirely given, that a player wears the same shoe during training, like during games, on the other hand, this is highly likely, given that it may be possible that a sprained ankle may have occured during training with another shoe type.
